  <h2>Decentralization as Political Architecture</h2>

  <p>
    Web3's core innovation isn't technological but political: it reimagines the relationship between
    users, platforms, and governance. By encoding rules in smart contracts rather than platform
    policies, Web3 shifts from the arbitrary power of corporate platforms to the deterministic
    governance of code.
  </p>

  <p>This shift raises critical questions:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Who writes the code that governs these systems?</li>
    <li>What values are encoded in the infrastructure?</li>
    <li>How is governance enacted and modified over time?</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    "Code is law, but who governs the code? The politics of Web3 infrastructure is not about
    eliminating governance, but relocating it from centralized institutions to decentralized
    protocols."
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Power Dynamics in Protocol Governance</h2>

  <p>
    The governance mechanisms of Web3 protocols often recreate familiar power structures.
    Token-weighted voting systems can concentrate decision-making power in the hands of large token
    holders, creating plutocratic governance structures that mirror existing economic inequalities.
  </p>

  <pre><code is:raw>// Example of a simple token-weighted voting contract
contract TokenVoting {
    mapping(address => uint256) public tokenBalance;
    mapping(uint256 => Proposal) public proposals;

    struct Proposal {
        uint256 id;
        string description;
        uint256 votesFor;
        uint256 votesAgainst;
        bool executed;
    }

    function vote(uint256 proposalId, bool support) public {
        // Voter's power is directly proportional to their token holdings
        uint256 votingPower = tokenBalance[msg.sender];

        if (support) {
            proposals[proposalId].votesFor += votingPower;
        } else {
            proposals[proposalId].votesAgainst += votingPower;
        }
    }
}</code></pre>

  <p>
    This simplified example illustrates how a token-weighted voting system encodes a specific
    political value: that influence should be proportional to capital investment. This is a
    political choice, not a technical necessity.
  </p>

  <h2>Infrastructure as Ideology</h2>

  <p>
    Web3 infrastructure is not value-neutral. The choice of consensus mechanisms, governance
    structures, and economic models all embed specific ideological assumptions about how digital
    societies should function.
  </p>

  <p>For example:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Proof-of-Work</strong> embeds a logic of competition and resource expenditure to establish
      trust
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Proof-of-Stake</strong> reinforces existing capital accumulation as the basis for governance
      rights
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Token Economics</strong> encode assumptions about incentives, rewards, and participation
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Beyond Techno-Determinism</h2>

  <p>
    The political implications of Web3 infrastructure are not predetermined by the technology
    itself. The same technical capabilities can serve radically different political ends depending
    on design choices, governance structures, and social contexts.
  </p>

  <p>
    As we design and deploy these systems, we need to recognize that we are not just building
    technical infrastructure, but political architecture that will shape how power, governance, and
    social coordination function in digital spaces.
  </p>

  <p>
    The politics of Web3 infrastructure demands a multidisciplinary approach that brings together
    technical expertise with political theory, economics, and social science to ensure that the
    systems we build reflect our collective values and aspirations.
  </p>
